{"slug": "druid", "root": "druid", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a nature-priest", "definition": "A druid is a priest of the ancient Celts — and, in fantasy, a nature-priest who draws magic from the living world. The word carries the forest with it.", "history": "*Druid* comes through Latin *druidēs* from Gaulish, on a Proto-Celtic root *dru-wid-*, 'oak-knower' or 'strong-seer' (*dru-*, oak/strong, + *weid-*, to see/know — the same *weid-* behind *wit* and *vision*). The historical druids left no writings; nearly everything romantic about them is later reconstruction. Magic's druids are green mana-priests, tending the mana of the land.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. druid", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Latin druidēs ← Gaulish ← Proto-Celtic *dru-wid- ‘oak-knower / strong-seer’", "first": "English 1560s", "note": "*dru- (‘oak’ / ‘strong’) + *weid- (‘to see, to know’). The same *weid- gives us wit, vision, and Sanskrit Veda.", "hook": "‘Oak-seer’: the tree hidden in ‘druid.’", "lang": "Celtic"}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 88, "oracle_total": 20, "in_flavor_cards": 86, "in_oracle_cards": 18, "name_match_count": 68, "by_variant": {"druid": 79, "druids": 29}, "first_year": 1994, "colors": {"G": 127, "U": 9, "B": 18, "W": 6, "C": 4, "R": 4}, "by_year": {"1994": 1, "1995": 5, "1996": 3, "1997": 4, "1998": 2, "2000": 1, "2001": 8, "2002": 7, "2003": 3, "2004": 2, "2005": 2, "2006": 7, "2007": 3, "2008": 8, "2009": 2, "2010": 3, "2011": 1, "2012": 3, "2013": 3, "2015": 3, "2016": 8, "2017": 2, "2018": 8, "2019": 2, "2020": 2, "2021": 15, "2022": 12, "2023": 6, "2024": 11, "2025": 14, "2026": 3}}, "cards": [{"id": "68cefb44-afad-4638-8fdc-65a099b51d55", "name": "Jenson Carthalion, Druid Exile", "se